    "abstract": "<jats:p>Background: Viral encephalitis refers to inflammation of the brain parenchyma caused by direct viral invasion or immune-mediated responses triggered by viral antigens and is a notifiable disease in Brazil. The COVID-19 pandemic, which began in 2020, posed challenges for epidemiological surveillance, as the virus became associated with neurological manifestations. Recent studies suggest that viruses such as Herpes and SARS-CoV-2 may act as immunological triggers for autoimmune encephalitis, which is often underdiagnosed or misinterpreted as infectious. The absence of a specific ICD-10 code data for autoimmune encephalitis further complicates case identification. Evaluating the trends in viral encephalitis-related hospitalizations during the COVID-19 pandemic may support discussions on the underdiagnosis of neuroimmunological conditions. Objective: To analyze the trend of hospital admissions for unspecified viral encephalitis (ICD-10 A86) in Brazil between 2019 and 2024, considering possible effects of the COVID-19 pandemic on case notifications and differential diagnosis with autoimmune encephalitis. Methods: This was an ecological, retrospective, cross-sectional study based on secondary data from the Brazilian Hospital Information System (SIH) covering the period from 2019 to 2024. Records of hospitalizations due to unspecified viral encephalitis were included and stratified by year and geographic region. Temporal trends and comparisons were conducted across three periods: pre-pandemic (2019), during the pandemic (2020–2021), and post-pandemic (2022–2024). Only records with complete data on date and location were considered; duplicate and inconsistent entries were excluded. Bar and line graphs were used to illustrate trends and regional distributions. Results: A total of 12,022 hospitalizations for unspecified viral encephalitis were recorded in Brazil between 2019 and 2024. A drop in hospitalizations was observed in 2020 (1,689 cases) and 2021 (1,647 cases), compared to 2,436 cases in 2019. From 2022 onwards, there was a steady increase: 1,977 cases in 2022, 2,072 in 2023, and 2,201 in 2024. The Northeast and Southeast regions had the highest number of hospitalizations, with 4,774 and 3,263 cases, respectively. Conclusion: Hospitalizations for viral encephalitis decreased in the first two years of the COVID-19 pandemic, possibly due to limited access to healthcare services and the reallocation of medical resources. The subsequent increase from 2022 may reflect the resurgence of neurotropic viral infections or undiagnosed autoimmune encephalitis cases presenting with similar clinical features. Current literature supports the hypothesis that SARS-CoV-2 may act as a trigger for autoimmune encephalitis, potentially contributing to the observed trend. These findings highlight the need for enhanced epidemiological surveillance and diagnostic capabilities to better differentiate between viral and autoimmune encephalitis and improve clinical outcomes.</jats:p>",
